'''Terry Wilcox''' (born {{circa}} 1940) is an American [[professional golfer]].

Wilcox grew up in [[Ada, Oklahoma]]. He played college golf at [[Oklahoma State University]], graduating in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/okst/sports/m-golf/auto_pdf/09mediaguide-section5.pdf |title=Championship History |work=Oklahoma State Men's Golf - 2009 Media Guide |page=157 }}</ref>

Wilcox turned professional in 1962. He played on the [[PGA Tour]] from 1964 to 1974<ref>{{cite book |editor=Sal Johnson and Dave Seanor |title=The USA Today Golfers Encyclopedia |year=2009 |publisher=[[Skyhorse Publishing]] |location=[[New York, New York]] |isbn=978-60239-302-8 |page=582 }}</ref> while also working as a club professional. His best finishes were a T-2 at the 1969 [[Azalea Open Invitational]] and a 2nd at the 1970 [[IVB-Philadelphia Golf Classic]]. His best finish in a [[men's major golf championships|major]] was a T-7 at the [[1969 PGA Championship]].

Wilcox served as tournament director of the [[Kraft Nabisco Championship]], an [[Women's major golf championships|LPGA major]], from 1994 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.golfdigest.com/golf-tours-news/2008-10/20081016siraksays |title=Kraft Nabisco's "Poppy" Steps Down |publisher=[[Golf Digest]] |date=October 17, 2008 |first=Ron |last=Sirak |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref>

==Professional wins==
''this list may be incomplete''
*1964 [[Westchester Open]]
*1965 [[Westchester Open]]
*1967 [[Metropolitan PGA Championship]]
*1974 [[North Carolina Open]], [[Carolinas PGA Championship]]
*1976 [[North Carolina Open]]

